Background:

Youve been hired as a data analyst at at football (soccer) club. Since this is a small and under-funded club, you will not have access to real-football data, but to data from the football computer game fifa18. Your job is to analyze this dataset and extract meaningful insights from the data in order to help your club make better decisions.

Data File:

You will load and analyze the fifa18 football dataset file called fifa_data.csv.
The dataset contains detailed information about each player in the game, including: names, age, nationality, overall ability, estimated potential ability, current club and league, market value, salary (wage), ability at different football skills (also called attributes, e.g.Ball.control, Sprint.speed ), ability to play at different position in the game (CF, CM, ) and the preferred positions of the player.

First, you are requested to load the fifa18 dataset and find and display general information about the players.

  1. Make a plot showing the overall ability distribution of all players. How skewed is the distributions? does it have fat tails?
    Plot on top of the overall distribution a Normal distribution matching its first two moments. Is the distribution described well by a Normal distribution? explain.

  2. Make a plot comparing the multiple overall ability distributions of players according to the continent of the players. Describe which continents have especially good/bad players.

  3. Make a plot showing the density of players value distribution.
    Next, make a separate plot showing the density distribution of the log of players value.
    Which of the two visualizations is better? explain.

  4. Are the top-10 players with the highest value also the top-10 best players in terms of overall ability? Show tables for both and compare.
    Who is the best player not in the top-10 valued players?

  5. Show a table of the 10 youngest and 10 oldest teams in terms of average players age.

Answer 1

a) a plot showing the overall ability distribution of all players. and a Plot on top of the overall distribution a Normal distribution matching its first two moments:

# two moments
mu <- round(mean(fifa_players$Overall),3)
sigma <- round(sd(fifa_players$Overall),3)

# Plot density 
norm_dist <- data.frame(x=seq(-4,4,len=1655)*sigma+mu) %>% mutate(density=dnorm(x,mu,sigma))

# 
ggplot(data = fifa_players,aes(x=Overall))+
geom_density(fill="#0099FF")+ # density   
xlab("Players' Overall")+
ylab("denisty")+
  labs(title="Players' Overall distribution by density")+
geom_line(aes(x, density),  data = norm_dist, lwd=1.5) # density of normal distrubition  

#skewness
print(round(skewness(fifa_players$Overall), 3))
## [1] 0.008
#kurtosis
print(kurtosis(fifa_players$Overall))
## [1] -0.02102
# check  if distrubition is normal by QQ plot
x<-fifa_players$Overall 
p <- seq(0.01, 0.99, 0.01)
observed_quantiles <- quantile(x, p)
theoretical_quantiles <- qnorm( p, mean = mean(x), sd = sd(x))
plot(theoretical_quantiles, observed_quantiles)
abline(0,1)

conclusion: the data are fairly symmetrical, although The skewness is positive (shows a very small right tail). also its time the data is fairly with no tails The kurtosis is negative, so we have short tails.

As we see the plots density is very similar. To make sure, I also ran a QQ- plot, that shows us that the points overlap the line. Therefore, the distribution is described well by a Normal distribution. _______________________________________________________________________________________

b) a plot comparing the multiple overall ability distributions of players according to the continent of the players:

ggplot(data = fifa_players,aes(x=Continent,y = Overall))+geom_boxplot()+
xlab("Continent")+ylab("Overall")+labs(title="Players' Overall Quality by Continent")

Conclusion: The dots that appear at the extreme tops and bottoms of each box plot represent the especially good and bad players in each continent. In Africa we have 1 especially good player, and 2 especially bad ones. In Asia we have 1 especially good player and no bad ones. In Europe we have 8 especially good players and no bad ones. In North America we have 4 especially good players, and 3 bad ones. In South America we have 7 good players, and 4 bad ones. _______________________________________________________________________________________

c) a plot showing the density of players value distribution:

# The density of players' value distribution.
ggplot(data = fifa_players,aes(x=Value))+
  geom_density()+
  labs(title="Players` value distribution")

a plot showing the density distribution of the log of players value:

# The density of log players' value distribution.

ggplot(data = fifa_players,aes(x=Value))+
  scale_x_continuous(trans='log10')+  
  geom_density()+
  labs(title="Players` log(value) distribution ")
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis
## Warning: Removed 227 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Conclusion: The log(value)is the better visualization, because the data have a very skewed distribution and the small number of very large values that can mislead in analysis. Although the log transformed data are still skewed, the skewness is much less and the data much easier to analyze. One very high value makes it very difficult to see the structure in the rest of the data. After the transformation, the variability becomes more similar to a normal distribution.

Q2. Scouting Report (30 pt)

You are in charge of the scouting division. The goal of this division is to follow players potential and overall ability, and identify undervalued players - that is, players whose current value is lower compared to what would be expected based on their predicted future ability.

  1. Plot the average potential ability by age of all players, for players 35 years old or younger

  2. Plot the average difference between a players overall ability to potential ability as a function of age, up to age 35. At what ages should we expect to find players for future development based on this graph?

  3. We are seeking young (\(age \leq 21\)) players with high potential (\(>70\)). Show a scatter plot of these players comparing their potential ability (x-axis) and current value (y-axis).
    Find the 10 most-undervalued players, i.e.having the lowest value compared to their predicted value by potential using a simple linear regression model.
    Calculate for each of them what is a fair value matching their potential that you be willing to pay in order to by them to your club and show these 10 players with their name, age, overall ability, potential, actual value and fair value it a table.

  4. Your boss wants to fly abroad to recruit promising players. Use the rworldmap package to display the world map and color each country based on the median potential of players from this nationality.

  5. Repeat the above analysis but this time display a world map where each country is colored by the median ratio of potential to value of players. Find an under-valued country youd recommend to travel to (i.e.a country with cheap players compared to their potential average quality).

potential_mean <- aggregate(fifa_players$Potential, by = list(fifa_players$Age),FUN = mean)

   xlab("Age")+
  ylab("Potential")+
  labs(title="Potential by Age") +
  geom_line()

potential_mean_young<-potential_mean[potential_mean$Group.1<=35,]

fifa$diffrence <- fifa$Potential-fifa$Overall

c) a scatter plot of these players comparing their potential ability (x-axis) and current value (y-axis) in order to find the proper value for the ten most undervalued players.

potential_value <- fifa_players[fifa_players$Overall>70 & fifa_players$Age<=21,]

lm_potential <- lm(Value ~ Potential, data=potential_value)
potential_value$resid <-resid(lm_potential) # The residuals show us the lowest value compared to their predicted value by potential.

#the most 10  undervalued players:
print(potential_value %>% arrange(resid) %>% select(Name, Age, Potential, Value, resid) %>% head(10))

## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Age'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
mean_pos<-mean_pos[mean_pos$Age<=35,] # conditions as q2

ggplot(data=mean_pos, aes(x=Age, y=mean_value, color=variable)) + 
  geom_line(size=1)+
  ggtitle("Player's Abilities VS Age") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))+
  facet_wrap(~variable  )+ 
  theme(legend.position="none")

Q4. Fix Problematic Plots (10 pt)

The previous data-analyst of the club was fired for producing poor plots. See below two bar plots that he made including their code.

  1. Describe in your own words what did your predecessor try to show in each of the two plots.
  2. Find at least three different problematic issues with his plots, and explain them.
  3. Fix the problematic issues above in the code below to generate new, improved plots.
    You will get an additional bonus point for finding any additional problem and fixing it.
    (identifying the same problem in the two plots counts as one problem).
# A measure of category's diversity
DIV <- function(category_vec){
  t <- table(category_vec)
  p <- t/sum(t)
  return(sum(p^2))
}

cleaned_data <- fifa_players %>% select(Nationality,Club) %>% na.omit()

number_of_nationality_in_club <- cleaned_data %>% group_by(Club, Nationality) %>% summarise(count = n()) %>% group_by(Club) %>% summarise(N_nation=n()) %>% arrange(desc(N_nation)) %>% mutate(Club = factor(Club, level=unique(Club)))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Club'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
DIV_in_club <- cleaned_data %>% group_by(Club) %>% summarise(DIV = DIV(Nationality))%>% arrange(DIV)%>% mutate(Club = factor(Club,level=unique(Club)))  # arrange(desc(DIV)) %>% 

# Plot number of different nationalities in each club
g <- ggplot(data = number_of_nationality_in_club %>% head(8), aes(x = Club, y = N_nation,color = Club))
g + geom_bar(stat="identity")

# Plot DIV (diversity?) of different nationalities in each club
g <- ggplot(data = DIV_in_club %>% head(12),aes(x = Club,y = DIV, color = Club))
g <- g + geom_bar(stat="identity")
g

Answer 4

a) The purpose of the plots is to find the clubs with the most varied nationalities. The first plot shows the 8 clubs with the greatest number of distinct nationalities in the club. The problem with the plot is that it takes no account of the fact that there are different numbers of players in each club. It is thus necessary to examine the ratio of nationalities in each club. Therefore, the second plot shows the ratio of nationalities for each of the top 12 clubs, using the function DIV (that calculate the index-of-coincidence). This plot shows the 12 clubs with the lowest ratio of nationalities per club.

b) The plots have the following problems: 1) The names of the clubs on the x axis are superimposed over each other. 2) The plots have no titles. 3) The variable DIV on the y axis is not sufficiently clear as to what is represents. 4) The plot contains a column representing NA, which should have been removed from the plot. 5) All the columns are colored in grey, making it difficult to distinguish the clubs represented in each column.

c) I fixed the problematic issues:
